  "body": "Hi there,\r\nI'm building Dockerfile that will download and run precompiled geth from https://ethereum.github.io/go-ethereum/downloads/ \r\nBut I want to run this image on different CPU architectures, so each time I need to download arch-specific geth image from https://ethereum.github.io/go-ethereum/downloads/\r\n\r\nMy current Dockerfile (working great on ARMv7 RPi3)\r\n```yaml\r\nFROM ubuntu:latest\r\n\r\n# Install wget\r\nRUN\tapt-get update \\\r\n    && apt-get install -y wget \\\r\n    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*\r\n\r\n#Download geth and copy into /usr/local/bin\r\nRUN    mkdir gethDownload \\\r\n    && wget -qO- https://gethstore.blob.core.windows.net/builds/geth-linux-arm7-1.8.1-1e67410e.tar.gz \\\r\n    | tar xvz -C gethDownload --strip-components 1 \\\r\n    && cd gethDownload \\\r\n    && mkdir -p /usr/local/bin \\\r\n    && mv geth /usr/local/bin/ \\\r\n    && cd .. \\\r\n    && rm -r gethDownload\r\n\r\nEXPOSE 8545 8546 30303 30303/udp 30304/udp\r\n\r\nENTRYPOINT [\"geth\"]\r\n```\r\nbut I would like to make it more generic. \r\nIs there any way to download latest stable version for my arch ?\r\nSomething like `wget \"https://ethereum.github.io/go-ethereum/downloads/$(uname -m)/latest/\"`\r\nYes, I know, it's easy to say, but just wondering if there is way to achieve it other way than hardcoding urls.\r\n\r\n",
